Foreshadowing the Future (or at least the present)

ROsenblatt's Perceptron

1957

The model was built to be similar to actual neurons

Albeit greatly simplified.

The Perceptron architecture:

(Go over the Perceptron)

Positive and negative weights

The input as image pixels

In 1957, this was all done by hand wired electronics:

But, the Perceptron had limitations


  • The lack of computing power at the time and the generally limited state of digital electronics.
  • There were certain types of problems - non-linearly separable - that you could prove it couldn't solve.


In their 1969 book, Perceptrons, Minsky and Seymour Papert pointed out these problems.


This effectively killed work on Perceptrons, and all types of artificial neural network models until the mid 1980s.

AI Winter

cf. Nuclear Winter

Image from: https://www.actuaries.digital/2018/09/05/history-of-ai-winters/

Expert Systems

Rule based computer program that tried to capture and use human expertise on tasks.

They could work well - e.g. IBM's Deep Blue system that in 1996 defeated the world champion Gary Kasparov in chess.

They had significant shortcomings:

  • They had to be created by hand. Every case, every scenario, every contingency had to be manually coded into them.
  • This made them narrow in scope, and often brittle.
  • They did not scale well.

Neural Networks and Deep Learning

In the 1980s, several researchers revived and revised an artificial neural networks (ANN) style of AI.

One that was centered on machine learning(ML).

Weaknesses of early ANN models:

  • Lack of computing power
  • Inability to learn and/or represent certain classes of problems.

By the mid 1980s, solutions were forthcoming for both of these problems.

With the advent of seminconductors (basically computers and related electronics on chips) Moore's Law was observed. That is, every 18 months the number of transistors that could be put on a computer (memory, etc.) chip doubled.

This results in increased speed and computing power for chip based computers. This took care of the first problem (and still is...)

in 1986, David Rumlhart, Geoffrey Hinton, and Ronald Williams published their work on error backpropagation. This was a generalization of the way that the Perceptron worked. But, it could deal with much more complex classes of problems.

Within a few years, backpropagation-based machine learning systems had become the dominant model in AI. And have remained so ever since.

Other trend and discoveries from around the same time have led us to the modern main trends in machine learning.

  • Kunihiko discovered pattern recognition techniques that became the basis for convolutional neural networks (CNN).
  • John Hopfield laid the basis for recurrent neural networks - networks that can handle sequences of data (e.g. a series of images).
  • Yann LeCun joined convolutional neural networks with backpropagation. This became the basis for modern deep learning.
  • Later, LeCun made significant improvements into how the backpropogation algorithms work (added descent algorithms).
  • Slightly different, but becoming increasingly important, Christopher Watkins, invented Q-Learning. This was an important foundation for reinforcement learning. In recent years, similar to LeCun's merger of backpropogation with CNNs to create deep learning, deep learning is merging with reinforcement learning to create Deep Reinforcement Learning to help solve additional types of problems.

Factors Contributing to AI/ML today

In addition to the algorithms, several things are contributing to the popularity/utility of AI/ML today.

  • Data - these machine learning models need data to learn from. The near universal use of computers (and data gaterhing sensors like cameras) provides this necessary data.
  • Lots of fast computers, storage capacity, and high-speed networks. The infrastructure that holds this all together.
  • GPUs - graphics processing units. These were originally were created to render computer graphics in video games. but, these same calculations, and the ability to do them in parallel make them also useful for AI/ML learning and calculations. (And for crypto mining, but that's a different story...)
